  <subfield code="m">(I) (Chain rule) If two maps f:U\to \mathcal{Y} and g:\mathcal{Y}\to \mathcal{Z} are Gâteaux differentiable, then their composition g\circ f is also Gâteaux differentiable, and \begin{equation*} \begin{align*} \begin{eqnarray}&amp;&amp;D\left(g\circ f\right)(x)[v]=Dg\left(\,f(x)\right)\left[Df(x)[v]\right]\end{eqnarray} \end{align*} \end{equation*} holds for all x\in U and v\in \mathcal{X}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">(II) (Product rule) Let \tau be a bilinear map from the product of two Banach spaces {{\mathcal{Y}}_{1}} and {{\mathcal{Y}}_{2}} into \mathcal{Z}. If two maps f:U\to {{\mathcal{Y}}_{1}} and g:U\to {{\mathcal{Y}}_{2}} are Gâteaux differentiable, then \tau \left(\,f,g\right)(x):=\tau \left(\,f(x),g(x)\right) is also Gâteaux differentiable, and</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\begin{equation*} \begin{align*} \begin{eqnarray}&amp;&amp;D\left(\tau \left(\,f,g\right)\right)(x)[v]=\tau \left(Df(x)[v],g(x)\right)+\tau \left(\,f(x),Dg(x)[v]\right)\end{eqnarray} \end{align*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\end{equation*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">holds for all x\in U and v\in \mathcal{X}. As a special case, let {{\mathcal{Y}}_{1}}={{\mathcal{Y}}_{2}}:=\mathcal{L}\left(\mathcal{H}\right) and let \tau be the usual product of two operators denoted by. Then we obtain</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\begin{equation*} \begin{align*} \begin{eqnarray}&amp;&amp;D\left(\,f\centerdot g\right)(x)[v]=Df(x)[v]\centerdot g(x)+f(x)\centerdot Dg(x)[v]\end{eqnarray} \end{align*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\end{equation*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">for all x\in U and v\in \mathcal{X}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
